<div class="slide">
    <div class="slide-meta">
        <span class="ch-tag">Chapter 3 À Automatic Behaviors</span>
        <span class="file-badge">Data/AppDbContext.cs</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="slide-h">Global Query Filters</h1>
    <p class="slide-p">
        Automatically append <code>WHERE IsDeleted = 0 AND SiteId = @@p</code> to every query &mdash;
        no manual <code>WHERE</code> in service code, ever. Two ways to set it up.
    </p>

    <div class="slide-grid-2">

        <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1rem;">
            <div class="card-s">
                <span class="badge-label badge-label--info">Direct &mdash; simple, easy to follow</span>
                <pre class="code"><code><span class="cm">// OnModelCreating ù register per entity</span>
modelBuilder.<span class="mt">Entity</span>&lt;<span class="tp">Product</span>&gt;()
    .<span class="mt">HasQueryFilter</span>(p =&gt;
        !p.IsDeleted
        &amp;&amp; p.SiteId == _svc.SiteId);

<span class="cm">// Every query now becomes:</span>
<span class="cm">// SELECT ... FROM Products</span>
<span class="cm">// WHERE IsDeleted = 0 AND SiteId = @@p</span>

<span class="cm">// Opt-out when needed:</span>
ctx.Products
    .<span class="mt">IgnoreQueryFilters</span>()
    .<span class="mt">ToListAsync</span>();</code></pre>
            </div>
            <div class="callout callout--warn">
                New entity? You must come back here and register another filter.
                Nothing reminds you &mdash; a missed entity silently leaks data or returns ghost rows.
            </div>
        </div>

        <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1rem;">
            <div class="card-s card-s--good">
                <span class="badge-label badge-label--good">Interface-driven &mdash; automatic &amp; fail-safe</span>
                <pre class="code"><code><span class="cm">// Step 1: marker interfaces</span>
<span class="kw">public interface</span> <span class="tp">ISoftDelete</span>  { <span class="kw">bool</span> IsDeleted { <span class="kw">get</span>; <span class="kw">set</span>; } }
<span class="kw">public interface</span> <span class="tp">IHaveSiteId</span> { <span class="kw">int</span>  SiteId    { <span class="kw">get</span>; } }

<span class="cm">// Step 2: implement on entity ù that IS the setup</span>
<span class="kw">public class</span> <span class="tp">Invoice</span> : <span class="tp">ISoftDelete</span>, <span class="tp">IHaveSiteId</span> { ... }

<span class="cm">// Step 3: one loop in OnModelCreating</span>
<span class="cm">// handles ALL present and future entities</span>
<span class="kw">foreach</span> (<span class="kw">var</span> type <span class="kw">in</span> mb.Model.<span class="mt">GetEntityTypes</span>()
    .<span class="mt">Where</span>(t =&gt; !t.<span class="mt">IsOwned</span>())
    .<span class="mt">Select</span>(t =&gt; t.ClrType))
{
    <span class="kw">var</span> filter = <span class="mt">BuildFilter</span>(type);
    <span class="kw">if</span> (filter <span class="kw">is not null</span>)
        mb.<span class="mt">Entity</span>(type).<span class="mt">HasQueryFilter</span>(filter);
}
<span class="cm">// New entity? Just implement the interface.</span>
<span class="cm">// AppDbContext never needs touching.</span></code></pre>
            </div>
            <div class="callout callout--good">
                <strong>Compiler-enforced.</strong> Forget to implement <code>IHaveSiteId</code> on a new entity
                and a code review will catch it &mdash; not a production incident.
            </div>
        </div>

    </div>
</div>
